.RE
.B
\fBopen(Host :: string() | inet:ip_address(), Opts) ->\fR
\fB              {ok, Client :: client()} | {error, Reason :: term()}\fR
\fB              when\fR
\fB                  Opts :: [Opt],\fR
\fB                  Opt :: StartOption | OpenOption,\fR
\fB                  StartOption :: {verbose, Verbose} | {debug, Debug},\fR
\fB                  Verbose :: boolean(),\fR
\fB                  Debug :: disable | debug | trace,\fR
\fB                  OpenOption ::\fR
\fB                      {ipfamily, IpFamily} |\fR
\fB                      {port, Port :: port()} |\fR
\fB                      {mode, Mode} |\fR
\fB                      {tls, TLSOptions :: [ssl:tls_option()]} |\fR
\fB                      {tls_sec_method, TLSSecMethod :: ftps | ftpes} |\fR
\fB                      {tls_ctrl_session_reuse,\fR
\fB                       TLSSessionReuse :: boolean()} |\fR
\fB                      {timeout, Timeout :: timeout()} |\fR
\fB                      {dtimeout, DTimeout :: timeout()} |\fR
\fB                      {progress, Progress} |\fR
\fB                      {sock_ctrl, SocketCtrls} |\fR
\fB                      {sock_data_act, [SocketControl]} |\fR
\fB                      {sock_data_pass, [SocketControl]},\fR
\fB                  SocketCtrls :: [SocketControl],\fR
\fB                  IpFamily :: inet | inet6 | inet6fb4,\fR
\fB                  Mode :: active | passive,\fR
\fB                  Module :: atom(),\fR
\fB                  Function :: atom(),\fR
\fB                  InitialData :: term(),\fR
\fB                  Progress :: ignore | {Module, Function, InitialData},\fR
\fB                  SocketControl :: gen_tcp:option().\fR

.RS
.LP
Deprecated: ftp:open/2 is deprecated; Legacy protocol support will be dropped in OTP-30, use more modern approach for file transfer as for instance SFTP (SSH File Transfer Protocol).
.RE

.br
.RS
.PP
Starts a FTP client process and opens a session with the FTP server at \fIHost\fR.

.PP
A session opened in this way is closed using function \fIclose/1\fR.

.PP
The available configuration options are as follows:

{host, Host}
.RS 2
Host = 
\fIstring() | ip_address()\fR

.RE

{port, Port}
.RS 2
Default is 
\fI0\fR which aliases to \fI21\fR or \fI990\fR when used with \fI{tls_sec_method,ftps}\fR).

.RE

{mode, Mode}
.RS 2
Default is 
\fIpassive\fR.

.RE

{verbose, Verbose}
.RS 2
Determines if the FTP communication is to be verbose or not.

.PP
Default is \fIfalse\fR.


.RE

{debug, Debug}
.RS 2
Debugging using the dbg toolkit.

.PP
Default is \fIdisable\fR.


.RE

{ipfamily, IpFamily}
.RS 2
With 
\fIinet6fb4\fR the client behaves as before, that is, tries to use IPv6, and only if that does not work it uses IPv4).
.PP
Default is \fIinet\fR (IPv4).


.RE

{timeout, Timeout}
.RS 2
Connection time-out.

.PP
Default is \fI60000\fR (milliseconds).


.RE

{dtimeout, DTimeout}
.RS 2
Data connect time-out. The time the client waits for the server to connect to the data socket.

.PP
Default is \fIinfinity\fR.


.RE

{tls, TLSOptions}
.RS 2
The FTP session is transported over 
\fItls\fR (\fIftps\fR, see RFC 4217). The list \fITLSOptions\fR can be empty. The function \fIssl:connect/3\fR is used for securing both the control connection and the data sessions.

.RE

{tls_sec_method, TLSSecMethod}
.RS 2
When set to 
\fIftps\fR will connect immediately with SSL instead of upgrading with STARTTLS. This suboption is ignored unless the suboption \fItls\fR is also set.
.PP
Default is \fIftpes\fR


.RE

{tls_ctrl_session_reuse, boolean()}
.RS 2
When set to 
\fItrue\fR the client will re-use the TLS session from the control channel on the data channel as enforced by many FTP servers as (proposed and implemented first by vsftpd).
.PP
Default is \fIfalse\fR.


.RE

{sock_ctrl, SocketCtrls :: [SocketControl :: gen_tcp:option()]}
.RS 2
Passes options from 
\fISocketCtrls\fR down to the underlying transport layer (tcp).
.PP
\fIgen_tcp:option/0\fR except for \fIipv6_v6only\fR, \fIactive\fR, \fIpacket\fR, \fImode\fR, \fIpacket_size\fR and \fIheader\fR.

.PP
Default value is \fISocketCtrls = []\fR.


.RE

{sock_data_act, [SocketControl]}
.RS 2
Passes options from 
\fI[SocketControl]\fR down to the underlying transport layer (tcp).
.PP
\fIsock_data_act\fR uses the value of \fIsock_ctrl\fR as default value.


.RE

{sock_data_pass, [SocketControl]}
.RS 2
Passes options from 
\fI[SocketControl]\fR down to the underlying transport layer (tcp).
.PP
\fIsock_data_pass\fR uses the value of \fIsock_ctrl\fR as default value.


.RE

{progress, Progress}
.RS 2
Progress = 
\fIignore | {Module, Function, InitialData}\fR
.PP
\fIModule = atom()\fR, \fIFunction = atom()\fR

.PP
\fIInitialData = term()\fR

.PP
Default is \fIignore\fR.

.PP
Option \fIprogress\fR is intended to be used by applications that want to create some type of progress report, such as a progress bar in a GUI. Default for the progress option is \fIignore\fR, that is, the option is not used. When the progress option is specified, the following happens when \fIftp:send/[3,4]\fR or \fIftp:recv/[3,4]\fR are called:


.sp
.RS 4
.ie n \{\
\h'-04'\(bu\h'+03'\c
.\}
.el \{\
.sp -1
.IP \(bu 2.3
.\}.PP
Before a file is transferred, the following call is made to indicate the start of the file transfer and how large the file is. The return value of the callback function is to be a new value for the \fIUserProgressTerm\fR that will be used as input the next time the callback function is called.

.PP
\fIModule:Function(InitialData, File, {file_size, FileSize})\fR

.RE


.sp
.RS 4
.ie n \{\
\h'-04'\(bu\h'+03'\c
.\}
.el \{\
.sp -1
.IP \(bu 2.3
.\}.PP
Every time a chunk of bytes is transferred the following call is made:

.PP
\fIModule:Function(UserProgressTerm, File, {transfer_size, TransferSize})\fR

.RE


.sp
.RS 4
.ie n \{\
\h'-04'\(bu\h'+03'\c
.\}
.el \{\
.sp -1
.IP \(bu 2.3
.\}.PP
At the end of the file the following call is made to indicate the end of the transfer:

.PP
\fIModule:Function(UserProgressTerm, File, {transfer_size, 0})\fR

.RE

.PP
The callback function is to be defined as follows:

.PP
\fIModule:Function(UserProgressTerm, File, Size) -> UserProgressTerm\fR

.PP
\fIUserProgressTerm = term()\fR

.PP
\fIFile = string()\fR

.PP
\fISize = {transfer_size, integer()} | {file_size, integer()} | {file_size, unknown}\fR

.PP
For remote files, \fIftp\fR cannot determine the file size in a platform independent way. In this case the size becomes \fIunknown\fR and it is left to the application to determine the size.

.PP
\fBNOTE: \fRThe callback is made by a middleman process, hence the file transfer is not affected by the code in the progress callback function. If the callback crashes, this is detected by the FTP connection process, which then prints an info-report and goes on as if the progress option was set to \fIignore\fR.


.PP
The file transfer type is set to the default of the FTP server when the session is opened. This is usually ASCII mode.

.PP
The current local working directory (compare \fIlpwd/1\fR) is set to the value reported by \fIfile:get_cwd/1\fR, the wanted local directory.

.PP
The return value \fIPid\fR is used as a reference to the newly created FTP client in all other functions, and they are to be called by the process that created the connection. The FTP client process monitors the process that created it and terminates if that process terminates.


.RE


